-- JC Tran Leads as Poker’s Main Event Cuts Field to November Nine
-- B y   M a s o n   L e v i n s o n
-- 2013-07-16T13:35:46Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2013-07-16/jc-tran-leads-as-poker-s-main-event-cuts-field-to-november-nine.html
JC Tran is the chip leader after the
 World Series of Poker  trimmed its main-event field to nine from
6,352.  Tran, a 36-year-old poker professional from  Sacramento ,
California, has 38 million chips to lead the $10,000 buy-in No-Limit Texas Hold’em World Championship at the Rio All-Suite
Hotel & Casino in  Las Vegas . He and eight others will return on
Nov. 4 to begin final-table play, crowning a 44th champion who
will receive almost $8.4 million.  Amir Lehavot, a 38-year-old Israeli poker pro living in
Weston, Florida, is second with 29.7 million chips. Marc
McLaughlin, a 25-year-old tattoo artist from Brossard,  Quebec ,
is third with about 26.5 million chips. McLaughlin finished 30th
in 2009 and 86th in 2011.  Others remaining are American Jay Farber, with 25.975
million chips; American Ryan Riess, with 25.875 million chips;
Frenchman Sylvain Loosli, with 19.6 million chips; Dutchman
Michiel Brummelhuis, with 11.275 million chips; American Mark
Newhouse, with 7.35 million chips; and American David Benefield,
with 6.375 million chips.  The  World Series  of Poker is a 62-event collection of
various types of poker tournaments that begins in May and ends
with the main event, which had a prize pool of $59.7 million.
The total prize pool of $197 million and 79,471 entrants for the
World Series each were records.  The ninth-place finisher will earn $733,227. Carlos
Mortensen, who won the event in 2001, finished 10th this year,
taking in $573,204.  To contact the reporter on this story:
Mason Levinson in  New York  at 
 mlevinson@bloomberg.net   To contact the editor responsible for this story:
